    wiki:"Thomas_Edison",
    overview:"Edison patented a practical incandescent bulb on October 22, 1879 after testing 6,000 materials for the filament. More important than the bulb: he designed an entire electrical system — generators, switches, meters, safety devices — to make it practical. Pearl Street Station (Manhattan, September 4, 1882) was the world's first commercial power plant, supplying electricity to 59 customers on a square-mile grid. The 'War of Currents' between Edison's DC and Westinghouse/Tesla's AC ultimately went to AC, which is still universal. Edison's Menlo Park was the world's first industrial research laboratory.",
    impact:["Electrification of civilization — replaced gas lighting, horse-drawn transportation (via electric trams), and steam power in factories","Edison's research lab model — teams of scientists solving specific commercial problems — became the standard for industrial R&D","'War of Currents' established AC power as the universal standard — Tesla/Westinghouse won","Without Edison's power grid, the 20th century's technology revolution would have been impossible"]
