    wiki:"Guglielmo_Marconi",
    overview:"Guglielmo Marconi, a young Italian, built on Hertz's electromagnetic wave demonstrations to create a practical radio transmitter and receiver. In 1897 he sent the first wireless message across water (the Bristol Channel). In 1901, using a kite aerial at Signal Hill in Newfoundland, he received the letter 'S' in Morse code sent from Cornwall — the first transatlantic radio transmission. Marconi's technology transformed maritime safety (the Titanic used radio distress signals in 1912) and became the foundation of all subsequent wireless communication.",
    impact:["Foundation of all wireless communication — radio, television, mobile phones, Wi-Fi, GPS","Titanic's distress signal used Marconi radio — saving ~710 lives despite the disaster","First transatlantic transmission (1901) proved electromagnetic waves followed Earth's curvature","Marconi's company became RCA — the dominant American broadcasting company of the 20th century"]
