    wiki:"X-ray",
    overview:"On November 8, 1895, Wilhelm Röntgen was experimenting with cathode rays when he noticed a fluorescent screen across the room glowing despite being shielded. He discovered a new type of radiation he called 'X-rays' (unknown rays). When he took an X-ray image of his wife's hand showing the bones clearly, she reportedly said: 'I have seen my own death.' Within weeks, physicians worldwide were using X-rays to locate bullets and set broken bones. Röntgen won the first Nobel Prize in Physics (1901)."
