    wiki:"ENIAC",
    overview:"ENIAC (1943–1945) was built at the University of Pennsylvania under John Mauchly and J. Presper Eckert to compute artillery firing tables for the US Army. Completed November 1945 (months after the war ended), it weighed 27 tons, occupied 1,800 square feet, used 17,468 vacuum tubes, and could perform 5,000 additions per second. It was programmed by six women ('The ENIAC Programmers' — Kathleen McNulty, Jean Jennings, etc.) whose contributions were long overlooked. ENIAC was 1,000 times faster than electromechanical computers.",
    impact:["First general-purpose electronic computer — ancestor of all subsequent computing","Programming by the six 'ENIAC women' pioneered software engineering — overlooked for decades","Transistors (1947) replaced vacuum tubes — enabling computers to shrink exponentially","Moore's Law predicts computers double in power every 2 years — ENIAC's 5,000 operations/second vs today's 100 trillion"]
