    wiki:"World_Wide_Web",
    overview:"Tim Berners-Lee, a British physicist at CERN, proposed the Web in 1989 to solve the problem of sharing scientific documents. He created HTML (the markup language), HTTP (the transfer protocol), and URLs (addresses), launching the first website on August 6, 1991. Crucially, he and CERN made the Web patent-free and open — allowing explosive growth. Mosaic (1993) and Netscape (1994) made the Web user-friendly. By 2000, the Web had transformed commerce, journalism, communication, and entertainment. Google (1998), Facebook (2004), and YouTube (2005) built on the open Web.",
    impact:["$50 trillion in internet-enabled commerce — built on technology given away for free","Wikipedia — freely available to anyone — the most comprehensive reference in human history","Google's search engine made all human knowledge practically findable in seconds","The Web's openness enabled extraordinary innovation; questions of who governs it remain unresolved"]
