    wiki:"CRISPR",
    overview:"CRISPR-Cas9 (Clustered Regularly Interspaced Short Palindromic Repeats) was developed as a gene-editing tool by Jennifer Doudna (UC Berkeley) and Emmanuelle Charpentier (Berlin) in 2012 — earning them the 2020 Nobel Prize in Chemistry. CRISPR allows precise cutting of DNA at specific sequences, enabling genes to be deleted, modified, or added. Applications include: sickle cell disease cure (FDA-approved, 2023), cancer immunotherapy, agricultural crop improvement, and potentially the elimination of genetic diseases.",
    impact:["First precise, affordable, scalable tool for editing any organism's genome","2023 FDA approval of CRISPR therapy for sickle cell disease — first gene-editing cure in history","Potential to eliminate thousands of inherited genetic diseases","Also raises profound ethical questions: 'designer babies,' germline editing, extinction of disease vectors","Charpentier-Doudna Nobel Prize (2020) — first all-female Nobel in Chemistry"]
