    overview:"After France's defeat in the Franco-Prussian War (1870–71) and the armistice that left 30,000 Prussian soldiers occupying Paris, Parisians refused to surrender their cannons and established a revolutionary municipal government (the Commune, March 18 – May 28, 1871). It introduced progressive measures: separation of church and state, free education, remission of rents, workers' control of factories. The French government retook Paris during 'Bloody Week' (May 21–28), killing 10,000–30,000 Communards. Marx analyzed the Commune as the first workers' state in his 'Civil War in France.'",
