    wiki:"First_Sino-Japanese_War",
    overview:"Competition over Korea triggered war in August 1894. Japan's modernized Meiji military — a product of 25 years of Western-style reform — destroyed China's Beiyang Fleet in three battles and defeated Chinese ground forces throughout Korea and Manchuria. The Treaty of Shimonoseki (1895) forced China to cede Taiwan, the Pescadores, and (briefly) the Liaodong Peninsula, pay massive reparations, and recognize Korean independence from Chinese suzerainty. The defeat shocked China — demonstrating that the Meiji model of modernization was the path Japan had proved it and motivating the Self-Strengthening Movement's more radical successors.",
    impact:["Revealed China's military weakness — sparked a generation of Chinese modernization efforts","Japan gained Taiwan (Japanese colony 1895–1945) and dominant position in East Asia","China forced to pay 230 million taels indemnity — roughly 3x Japan's annual national revenue","Humiliation directly caused the Hundred Days' Reform (1898) and Boxer Rebellion (1900) — and eventually the 1911 Revolution"]
